  <content>
    <title>Voice UI Design Basics</title>

    <summary>A process for designing voice user interfaces (VUI): write sample dialogues first, then extract intent/slot schemas, design prompts under 20 words, build a 3-attempt error recovery chain, and validate with Wizard of Oz testing before any NLU training begins.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Voice interfaces fail when designed like visual ones — unnatural prompts, missing error recovery, and idealized utterance sets that do not match real speech cause high abandonment. Writing dialogues before building schemas grounds the design in natural language and exposes confirmation strategy and context-tracking gaps before they become production bugs.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Designing a new voice feature for a mobile app, smart speaker skill, or IVR system</item>
        <item>Writing and reviewing dialogue scripts for conversational AI products</item>
        <item>Defining intent/slot schemas for NLU training (Alexa, Dialogflow, Rasa)</item>
        <item>Auditing existing voice flows for error handling gaps and confirmation strategy mismatches</item>
        <item>Generating utterance variations for NLU training data</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Complex data entry, browsing, or detailed comparison tasks — voice is the wrong modality</item>
        <item>Noisy environments or contexts requiring private information (credit card numbers, passwords)</item>
        <item>First-version MVP features where basic screen UI is not yet validated</item>
        <item>Platforms without microphone access or TTS output capability</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="step-1-define-use-cases">
      <p>Voice is a specialized interaction modality suited to specific task types.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Select voice for hands-free tasks, quick commands, simple queries, accessibility needs, and multitasking contexts only — not for complex data entry, private information, or browsing.</statement>
        <rationale>Voice adds a second interaction modality with significant design cost; applying it where it has no advantage over touch or keyboard wastes that investment.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-2-write-sample-dialogues">
      <p>Dialogue-first design is essential. Write natural conversation scripts before any schema work.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Write natural conversation scripts for happy path and top 3 error paths before designing any intent schema or building any NLU model.</statement>
        <rationale>Dialogue-first design grounds the schema in real language. Schema-first design produces idealized utterances that do not match natural speech, leading to poor NLU coverage in production.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Example happy path: User: "Set a timer for 15 minutes" / System: "Timer set for 15 minutes, starting now."</p>
      <p>Example error path: User: "Order pizza" / System: "Sure! Which pizza place? You've ordered from Papa's Pizza and Domino's before."</p>
    </section>

    <section name="step-3-define-intents-and-slots">
      <p>Intent and slot structure emerges from dialogue analysis, not vice versa.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Define each intent with required and optional slots, then generate at least 10 utterance variations per intent before NLU training; 20+ is the practical minimum for production.</statement>
        <rationale>Underrepresented utterance variation is the primary cause of NLU production failures. Agents generating training data produce syntactically varied but semantically homogeneous utterances — add real user quotes from research.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Intent structure: name, description, required slots (with reprompt if missing), optional slots, sample utterances, response template.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="step-4-design-prompts">
      <p>Spoken prompts have different constraints than written text.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Keep system prompts under 20 words for smart speakers, under 15 for IVR, under 30 for screen+voice hybrids; read every prompt aloud before approving.</statement>
        <rationale>Text that reads naturally in a document is often awkward when spoken; prompt length limits enforce spoken-word conventions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use implicit confirmation for low-risk actions and explicit confirmation for irreversible ones — never confirm every action (users abandon verbose confirmation flows).</statement>
        <rationale>Confirmation overhead is the leading cause of voice feature abandonment; calibrate confirmation strategy to action risk, not to developer anxiety.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-5-handle-errors">
      <p>Error recovery strategy separates successful voice features from abandoned ones.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Design a 3-attempt error recovery chain: 1st attempt rephrase the prompt; 2nd attempt offer examples; 3rd attempt offer a fallback path (agent transfer, visual alternative, or different action).</statement>
        <rationale>A missing third-attempt fallback leaves users stranded with no exit; they abandon the feature and do not return.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Error types to handle: no input, speech not recognized, intent not understood, slot value invalid, confirmation denied</item>
        <item>Never use "I'm sorry" as a standalone response — it acknowledges the error without offering resolution</item>
        <item>Never use URLs in voice prompts — they are unusable in audio context</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-6-test-with-users">
      <p>Wizard of Oz testing captures real speech variation that agent-generated utterance sets miss.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run Wizard of Oz testing (human playing system role) before any NLU training — intent schemas generated without real utterance data have poor production coverage.</statement>
        <rationale>WoZ testing captures natural speech variation, accent patterns, and implicit slot omissions that agent-generated utterance sets miss entirely.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Test with at least 3 different accents and 2 ambient noise levels before shipping to production.</statement>
        <rationale>STT recognition accuracy varies significantly across accents and noise levels; lab testing in a quiet studio is not representative of real-world usage.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="good-dialogue-examples">
      <p>Concrete examples of voice interface patterns that work.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Food ordering — happy path">
        <note>User: "Order my usual from Papa's Pizza" / System: "I'll place your usual order: a large pepperoni and a 2-liter Coke for delivery. That's $18.50. Should I place the order?" / User: "Yes" / System: "Order placed. Delivery in about 35 minutes." Explicit confirmation for high-value irreversible action; response confirms all order details before execution.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Food ordering — error recovery">
        <note>User: "Order pizza" / System: "Sure! Which pizza place? You've ordered from Papa's Pizza and Domino's before." / User: "Papa's" / System: "What would you like from Papa's Pizza?" System guides slot filling without demanding all information upfront; uses history to narrow disambiguation.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Smart home — utterance variation">
        <note>User: "Turn off the living room lights" / "Lights off in the living room" / "Living room lights off" / "Kill the lights in the living room" — all map to Intent: ControlLight, Slots: room=living room, action=off. Design accepts natural language variation, not just canonical phrasing.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <p>Common failure patterns in voice interface design.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Hollow apology as error response: "I'm sorry, I didn't understand that. Please try again."</description>
        <reason>Acknowledges the error without offering resolution. User does not know what to say differently. Use instead: "I didn't catch that. You can say a size like 'medium' or 'large'." — acknowledgment plus concrete guidance.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Prompt too long: "Hello! Welcome to Pizza Palace, the best pizza in town! We have so many great options today! What can I get for you?" (25+ words)</description>
        <reason>Long prompts in audio context cause users to forget the question before they can respond. Speakers optimize for silence-filling; good VUI designers optimize for response elicitation.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>URL in voice prompt: "You can find more information at www.pizzapalace.com/menu."</description>
        <reason>URLs are unusable in audio context. Users cannot transcribe a URL they hear. Use instead: "I'll send the menu link to your phone."</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Missing third-attempt fallback: system loops back to the original prompt after the second failed attempt with no alternative path offered.</description>
        <reason>Users stranded with no exit path abandon the voice feature entirely and do not return. The third attempt must always offer a different modality (human agent, visual fallback, different action).</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Single-utterance intent training: NLU model trained on one example phrase per intent.</description>
        <reason>Production NLU models with fewer than 10 utterances per intent fail on natural speech variation, accent differences, and informal phrasing. Coverage requires diversity of form, not just accuracy of one canonical form.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-limitations">
      <p>What agents cannot do in voice interface design.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Agents generate dialogue scripts that sound natural in text but are awkward when spoken aloud — always read prompts aloud before approving.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents do not simulate speech. Visual reading is not the same as hearing.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Intent/slot schemas generated without real user utterance data have poor NLU coverage; agents tend to write idealized utterances, not natural speech.</statement>
        <rationale>Training data quality depends on capturing real usage variation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Error recovery chains generated by agents are often too short (2 attempts, then fallback) or too long (endless reprompts).</statement>
        <rationale>Agents lack the conversation design intuition to calibrate recovery strategy.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Agents cannot simulate speech recognition errors, accent variation, or ambient noise — Wizard of Oz testing with real users is irreplaceable.</statement>
        <rationale>Real-world conditions cannot be captured in text.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Multi-turn dialogue context management is routinely under-designed by agents working from single-turn examples.</statement>
        <rationale>Context persistence requires understanding conversation flow, not individual turns.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Platform-specific constraints (Alexa response length, Google Assistant card limits) are often ignored in generated flows.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents lack knowledge of platform limits.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Using AI agents in voice interface design. An agent receives a use-case description and generates: (1) sample dialogues for happy path and top 3 error paths, (2) intent/slot schema in the target platform format (Alexa JSON, Dialogflow YAML, or Rasa NLU YAML), and (3) a set of 10-15 utterance variations per intent for NLU training. A second agent reviews for prompt length violations, confirmation strategy gaps, and missing fallback routes. Human Wizard of Oz testing validates before NLU training begins.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: General Claude subagent (opus) for dialogue script writing and intent schema design — these require nuanced language modeling. General Claude subagent (sonnet) for utterance variation generation for NLU training data.</p>

      <p>Prompt pattern: You are a VUI designer. Given this use case: [description]. Write: 1. Happy path dialogue (user + system turns, 4-6 turns max). 2. Error path #1: speech not recognized (3-attempt recovery chain). 3. Error path #2: slot value invalid (with examples offered to user). 4. Intent schema with required/optional slots and 10 utterance variations. Follow these constraints: each system prompt ≤20 words when spoken aloud; no "I'm sorry" as a standalone response; always offer an alternative path on 3rd error.</p>

      <p>Utterance variation generator prompt: Given this intent: [IntentName] with slots [slot1, slot2]. Generate 20 natural utterance variations that a real user might say. Include: different word orders, contractions, implicit slot omissions, informal speech. Flag any variation that might conflict with [list of other intents].</p>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-platforms">
      <p>Development tools and services for voice UI design and deployment.</p>

      <p>CLI tools: rasa (open-source NLU + dialogue management framework, pip install rasa / https://rasa.com/docs/). ask-cli (Alexa Skills Kit CLI — deploy and test Alexa skills, npm i -g ask-cli / https://developer.amazon.com/en-US/docs/alexa/smapi/ask-cli-intro.html). gactions (Google Actions CLI — build and test Google Assistant actions, https://developers.google.com/assistant/actionssdk/gactions). voiceflow-cli (export/import Voiceflow projects for CI/CD, https://www.voiceflow.com/blog/voiceflow-cli). botium (conversational AI testing framework with NLU assertions, npm i -g botium-cli / https://botium.ai).</p>

      <p>SaaS and specialized services: Voiceflow (SaaS with REST API for visual VUI design + NLU; API allows programmatic flow export/import). Dialogflow CX (SaaS enterprise NLU; agent-generated intents/flows can be pushed via API). Amazon Alexa Developer Console (SaaS with ASK API; skill manifest and interaction model as JSON; fully API-driven). Rasa (OSS on-prem NLU; agents can generate training data YAML and push to CI). Botmock (SaaS for VUI prototyping; partial REST API for project management). Deepgram (SaaS STT API with analytics; reveals real-world recognition error patterns).</p>
    </section>

    <note>
      Best practices: Write dialogues in spoken form first, then extract intents — never design intents before writing dialogues. Keep system prompts under 20 words for smart speakers; under 15 for IVR; under 30 for screen+voice hybrids. Every intent needs at minimum 10 utterance variations before NLU training; 20+ is the practical minimum for production. Use implicit confirmation for low-risk actions, explicit for irreversible ones — never confirm everything (users abandon verbose confirmation). Design the third-error fallback before designing the happy path — fallbacks are where voice UIs fail most visibly. Test with at least 3 different accents and 2 ambient noise levels before shipping.
    </note>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/voice-flow.md" purpose="Full voice flow document: user context, happy path, intent definitions, error handling, confirmation strategy, edge cases, fallbacks"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-writing.md" purpose="Prompt design template with primary, variations, reprompts (3 levels), and A/B test variants"/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/vui-lint.py" purpose="Python linter for VUI dialogue scripts: checks prompt length, detects hollow apologies, URLs, and long numbers"/>
    </scripts>

